purpose of closing this chapter with a few musings, -- musings upon no topic in particular. They may be somewhat sad in this tone; but then, sadness is not a new feature among these pages. We read in Scripture that "out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaketh;" & to the divine precept I add that, whether it be with words of sadness or words of joy. The mouth is the speaking trumpet of the heart; & he is blessed indeed, whose heart is true that the words may be good. Our summer is passing away -- swiftly, & upon silent wings. I am not enjoying it as I thought to do, long months ago, when 
"Spring, like an Angel of beauty, was here."
Perhaps, to some extent, it is my own fault, but then, it is nothing new for one to be disappointed. One of my every day privileges is to sit out in the yard, under a willow tree in my old chair. The sunshine is fine & glorious -- the breezes soft & sweet; & what little there is around me of green grass & leafy shade, rests & soothes me. I gaze up into the far-off sky, at times so blue & calm, at others, so dark & stormy. And I know that up, higher than the highest changing clouds, there is an eternal calm, rest & life. I often wheel my chair near the front gates, where I naturally fall to watching the passers-by. They are continually passing too & fro, mingled with many a little child. In form & face, some of them are fair & youthful; others are worn & aged. Some of them I know;
